data.title: Roy Orbison's hologram makes his musical comeback from beyond the grave in a national tour
data.meta_description: The rock icon died 30 years ago from a heart attack at age 52 but is being digitally resurrected for a 28-show US tour, playing his greatest hits as a hologram.
data.text:
Roy Orbison has kicked off his national tour from beyond the grave.

The rock legend took the stage as a hologram Tuesday night in Los Angeles to begin his 28-stop tour through the US.

The 'In Dreams' tour shows Orbison in his glory days, rising from the stage with a red Gibson guitar in hand, dark sunglasses on and sporting a grey suit while a full live orchestra plays his greatest hits.

Despite dying 30 years ago of a heart attack at 52, the Pretty Woman singer is making a comeback with 'newly recorded, never-before-heard, digitally remastered arrangements of his classics'.

'This is as good as seeing him in person as you'll ever get,' Ray Sadowski, 71, told the LA Times of Tuesday night's concert.

Sadowski paid about $200 for a pair of tickets to the 65-minute show that features 16 songs.

Orbison appeared on stage singing classics, including In Dreams, It's Over, Only the Lonely, Crying and Oh, Pretty Woman.

It is one of the first full-length concerts to feature a deceased singer, after an appearances by the late rapper Tupac Shakur stunned the crowd when he appeared at the 2012 Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival.

The trend continued with stars including Billie Holiday and the King of Pop Michael Jackson being digitally resurrected.

Earlier this year, BASE Hologram, the company behind the technology, sold 38,000 tickets for the Orbison hologram's European tour.

'Our goal for this type of show is not just to play in major metropolitan cities, but to bring this experience to a variety of markets, regardless of size,' Brian Becker, the founder and CEO of BASE Entertainment and BASE Hologram, said in a statement.

'We also want to give fans across the globe the unique opportunity to once again experience the legend who continues to be a pivotal force in Rock 'n' Roll music and ensure that people in every city, in every type of venue, have a chance to witness what we truly believe is the future of live entertainment,' Becker said.

The singer and songwriter died at the age of 52 following a heart attack while visiting his mother in Hendersonville, Tennessee.

His life was rocked with family tragedy with his wife Claudette dying in a 1966 motorcycle accident; in 1968, a fire at his Nashville home killed two of the couple's three children while he was away on tour.

'My father had a special transcendent vocal ability that made him something of an anomaly in the world of pop and rock, but that's what endeared him to his fans,' Alex Orbison, Roy's son and President of Roy Orbison Music, previously said of the hologram.

'For our family it was an amazing emotional experience to see this for the first time and we know audiences worldwide will have the same reaction.'

After the tour ends, the Orbison's hologram will have a residency at Brandon, Missouri's Andy Williams Moon River Theatr beginning in 2019.

This will be the first ever hologram residency.
